.SH NAME
lambda \- lambda calculus beta-reduction playground
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lambda
.RI [ OPTION ...]
.RI [ EXPR ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lambda
starts an interactive ncurses lambda calculus reducer when no expression is
given. With one or more expressions, it reduces each expression on standard
output and exits.
.PP
Expressions use normal-order beta reduction. Final result lines are numbered
as
.BR [N]> .
Backslash and the UTF-8 lambda character both introduce abstractions.
In the interactive interface, a trailing
.B /
or
.BI / N
performs gradual reduction by one or
.I N
steps; a displayed
.B (...)
means more beta steps remain.
.PP
When a displayed term is alpha-equivalent to one or more saved definitions,
.B lambda
shows those definition names in brackets beside the term.
If a name is followed by
.BR * ,
the saved definition reduces to the displayed term.
When evaluating a saved name,
.B lambda
shows the saved expression before recursively expanding it and reducing.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-d,\ --define\  NAME=TERM
Save a lazy named definition before reducing expressions. Definitions may be
used by later expressions in the same invocation.
.TP
.BI \-d,\ --define\  NAME<-TERM
Reduce
.I TERM
first, then save the result as
.IR NAME .
.TP
.BI \-e,\ --eval\  EXPR
Reduce
.IR EXPR .
.TP
.BI \-f,\ --free\  NAME
Forget a definition saved earlier in the same invocation.
.TP
.BI \-l,\ --load\  FILE
Load definitions from
.IR FILE .
Use
.B --load std
to load the standard library from
.BR std.lc .
The file is read line by line; blank lines and lines starting with
.B #
are ignored.
.TP
.BI --max-steps\  N
Stop reducing after
.I N
steps. The default is 300.
.TP
.B \-h, --help
Show usage information.
.TP
.B \-V, --version
Show version information.
.SH INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
.TP
.B :defs
Show saved definitions.
.TP
.BI :def\  NAME
Show the saved definition named
.IR NAME
without expanding it. For eager definitions saved with
.BR <- ,
also show the original expression as it was defined.
.TP
.BI :free\  NAME
Forget a saved definition, making the name free again.
.TP
.BI :load\  FILE
Load definitions from
.IR FILE
without printing each imported definition. After loading, use
.B :defs
to see manual definitions first and loaded definitions grouped by filename.
Use
.B :load std
to load the standard library from
.BR std.lc .
Quoted paths and backslash escapes are accepted, for example
.B ":load \(dqmy file.lc\(dq"
or
.BR ":load my\\ file.lc" .
Leading
.B ~/
is expanded to the current user's home directory.
.TP
.BI :max-steps\  N
Set the reduction step limit for later interactive reductions. With no
argument,
.B :max-steps
shows the current limit. The default is 300 steps.
.TP
.B :clear
Clear the terminal and scrollback.
.TP
.B :help
Show interactive help.
.TP
.B :version
Show version information.
.TP
.B :q
Quit.
.SH INTERACTIVE KEYS
.TP
.B PageUp, PageDown
Scroll through previous interactive output.
.TP
.B Mouse wheel
Scroll through previous interactive output when supported by the terminal.
.SH SYNTAX
.TP
.B \ex.x
Abstraction. In the interactive interface, typing backslash is displayed as
lambda.
.TP
.B x y z
Application. Application is left associative, so this means
.BR "(x y) z" .
.TP
.B f \ex.x
Bare lambda abstractions may be used as application arguments. This means
.BR "f (\ex.x)" .
.TP
.B xx
Lowercase letters split into variables, so this means
.BR "x x" .
.TP
.B x1 x2
Subscript-style variables. The interactive interface displays them as
.BR "x\[u2081] x\[u2082]" .
.TP
.B KI, Ki
Uppercase-starting names remain single identifiers and are useful for saved
definitions.
.TP
.B %
Previous numbered output result.
History references are reserved and cannot be lambda parameters.
.TP
.BI % N
Result from numbered output line
.IR N .
.TP
.B TERM /
Reduce
.I TERM
by one beta step and stop.
.TP
.BI TERM\ / N
Reduce
.I TERM
by
.I N
beta steps and stop.
.TP
.BI / N
Continue the previous gradual reduction by
.I N
steps. A bare
.B /
or empty input continues by one step.
.SH STANDARD LIBRARY
Load the standard library with
.B :load std
or
.BR "--load std" .
It includes common combinators and aliases such as
.BR I ,
.BR K ,
.BR S ,
.BR Id ,
.BR Compose ,
and
.BR Flip ;
Church booleans such as
.BR True ,
.BR False ,
.BR And ,
.BR Or ,
.BR Not ,
.BR Xor ,
.BR Implies ,
and
.BR BoolEq ;
Church numerals
.BR Zero
through
.BR Twelve ;
arithmetic and comparisons such as
.BR Succ ,
.BR Pred ,
.BR Add ,
.BR Plus ,
.BR Mul ,
.BR Times ,
.BR Exp ,
.BR Pow ,
.BR Sub ,
.BR Eq ,
.BR Lt ,
.BR Lte ,
.BR Gt ,
.BR Gte ,
.BR Min ,
.BR Max ,
.BR Even ,
and
.BR Odd ;
pairs such as
.BR Pair ,
.BR Fst ,
.BR Snd ,
.BR First ,
.BR Second ,
.BR Swap ,
.BR Curry ,
and
.BR Uncurry ;
and Church-list helpers such as
.BR Nil ,
.BR Empty ,
.BR Cons ,
.BR Singleton ,
.BR Foldr ,
.BR Map ,
.BR Filter ,
.BR Append ,
.BR Concat ,
.BR Length ,
.BR IsNil ,
.BR Head ,
.BR Tail ,
.BR Any ,
.BR All ,
and
.BR Reverse .
.PP
Primed recursive variants such as
.BR Add' ,
.BR Foldr' ,
and
.BR Map'
are also provided for comparison with the direct definitions.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B lambda '(\ex.x) y'
Reduce an expression and print each step.
.TP
.B lambda -d 'I=\ex.x' 'I y'
Save a definition and use it in a later expression.
.TP
.B I = \ex.x
In the interactive interface, save a lazy definition.
.TP
.B I <- (\ex.x) y
In the interactive interface, reduce first and save the result as
.BR I .
.TP
.B :load std
Import definitions from
.BR std.lc .
.TP
.B :def I
Show the saved definition named
.BR I .
.TP
.B :free I
Remove the saved definition named
.BR I .
.TP
.B lambda -d 'I=\ex.x' -d 'J=\ey.y' '\ez.z'
Show that
.B \ez.z
is alpha-equivalent to the saved definitions
.B I
and
.BR J .
